<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/f89e25d0f86d6f1cbc63ffde3ee51b0e> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Chilkat blanket; Tlingit; 1880-1920\r\nMountain goat wool, yellow cedar fiber, pigments; 175 x 113 x 53 cm.   \r\nRMV 2935-5; formerly Lévi-Strauss collection; museum purchase at Hotel Drouot auction, Paris 1951\r\n\r\nChilkat textiles, with their intricate crest images, were symbols of wealth and prestige that only the highest-ranking people in Northwest Coast communities could afford. A costume consisting entirely of Chilkat weavings was the ultimate high status dress of which the blanket was the focal point. Only the wealthiest chiefs owned Chilkat blankets or gave them away during potlatches, sometimes cut into pieces and distributed among the high-ranking guests. The garment functioned as a status symbol till the very end. After his death, a chief was laid in state, dressed in his blanket and surrounded with his prestige objects and other valuables (Samuel 1982:27,35-36). \r\n\r\nChilkat blankets developed from earlier textiles such as Raven’s Tail with which geometric designs were made in the weavings. At the beginning of the nineteenth century, Tsimshian weavers invented a twining technique that made the weaving of circles, ovals and contours possible. From then on weavers incorporated crest images in textiles. All the Northern Coastal peoples practiced this weaving technique, done by hand without the use of tools. But by the end of the nineteenth century only Tlingit women from the Chilkat area continued to weave in this tradition (Jonaitis 2006:138).\r\n\r\nGathering and preparing of materials took many months. For the warp and the weft mountain goat wool was used, and the average Chilkat blanket required three fleeces.  Only the soft down under the guard hairs was used, and it was much warmer and softer than the Merino wool the early European traders compared it with. In contrast to previous weaving traditions, the warp threads contained a core of the inner bark of the yellow cedar. Spinning was done by hand on the knee, but spindle whorls were known and used by the Tlingit, although undecorated and smaller than those used by the Coast Salish. The blankets were originally woven in three colors, black, white and yellow, derived from vegetal and mineral pigments. In the nineteenth century synthetic dyes came into use (Samuel 1982:52-55,62,66-67).\r\n\r\nChilkat weaving was done in collaboration between men and women. Men painted the design, which consisted of a central panel and one side panel, on a wooden board while the women wove the image in the blanket. It was an exact copy of the painted pattern with the addition of a second side panel which was a symmetrical view of the example that was drawn on the pattern board. The board was very valuable and could be used several times by the same weaver. It took a weaver about six months to complete weaving a Chilkat blanket, combining work on the blanket with her daily household tasks. Chilkat weaving was probably an inherited privilege from the mother or grandmother (Samuel 1982:25,45). \r\n\r\nAlthough the Chilkat blanket is decorated with crest images, it is often hard or even impossible to identify and interpret the individual figures. Lt. George T. Emmons collected Chilkat patterns and their names among the Tlingit and while using his work as a reference we might call the figure on the central panel ‘diving whale’, with the human face in the centre as the whale’s body, and the figures on either side panel a ‘young sitting raven.’ Whatever the identification of the images, their interpretation may vary and their original identity might never be unraveled (Emmons 1907:376; Samuel 1982:39).\r\n\r\nIndian arts initially flourished as novel European tools gave artists opportunity to expand on traditional techniques. The appeal of European items resulted ultimately in the decline of Indian crafts, as factory made products proved to be cheaper and easier to use or wear, as well as have more appeal for their exotic, prestigious, and modern qualities. At the beginning of the twentieth century, the number of women who were able to weave the complex Chilkat blanket declined. The last Tlingit woman who learned this art from an experienced weaver was Jennie Thlunaut (1891-1986), and she passed this tradition on to a new generation (Jonaitis 2005:265). In 1993 textile artist Irene Jonker traveled from The Netherlands to Alaska to learn to weave Chilkat and Raven’s Tail in Juneau and Ketchikan. Subsequently she did demonstrations and workshops in her native country.\r\n\r\nMette van der Hooft\r\nRijksmuseum voor Volkenkunde, Leiden, NL\r\n\r\nGeorge T. Emmons, The Chilkat Blanket; Memoirs of the American Museum of Natural History 3; New York, 1907. Aldona Jonaitis, Art of the Northwest Coast; University of Washington Press; Seattle, 2006. Cheryl Samuel, The Chilkat Dancing Blanket; University of Oklahoma Press; Norman, 1982.\r\n\r\n\r\nChilkat deken, genoemd naar de Chilkat, een regionale groep van de Tlingit stam, die het \r\nmeest bedreven waren in het maken van deze dekens van de wol van bergschapen of het langste met deze traditie voortgingen. Ook andere Tlingit-groepen weefden dergelijke dekens, evenals de Haida en Tsimshian. Bij deze laatste groep ligt de oorsprong van de dekens.\r\nMannen schilderden de patronen op houten panelen, meestal slechts één helft, aangezien beide helften steeds het spiegelbeeld van elkaar vormen. Zij leverden drie vachten van bergschapen voor een deken. De dieren werden in de herfst en winter geschoten als hun vacht het dichtste was.\r\nVrouwen verwerkten de patronen bij het weven. De schering bestond uit met bergschapenwol omwikkelde vezels van bij voorkeur de gele ceder. De patronen zijn gestileerde representaties van dieren en mythologische wezens waarmee een afstammingsrelatie bestaat. De abstractie gaat vaak zo ver dat hun identiteit soms moeilijk is vast te stellen.\r\nDe garens werden geverfd. Zwart werd verkregen door de wol zeven dagen te laten weken en gisten in een oplossing van \"hemlock\"-bast en urine, waarna het geheel werd gekookt. Vervolgens ging de zwarte wol in een bad met urine en een stuk koper waarin het kort werd gekookt om de kleur te laten hechten op de wol. Geel werd verkregen van een kooksel van wolfsmos, een korstmos die in het binnenland op bomen groeit. De blauwgroene kleur werd verkregen uit een bad in koperoxide, gevolgd door een bad in wolfsmos.\r\nDergelijke schouderdekens waren erg kostbaar en alleen de elite kon zich deze permitteren en bracht er de eigen hoge sociale status mee tot uitdrukking. Het centrale paneel kwam goed uit omdat het op de rug hing; de twee zijpanelen hingen om de schouders en bovenarmen.\r\nOp de meeste Chilkat dekens vertegenwoordigt het centrale paneel een \"duikende walvis\", zij het in vergaande mate gestileerd (ook in dit geval?)." .
